The paper deals with algorithms for solving the Closest Vector Problem (CVP) on Euclidean lattices, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and has applications in cryptography, coding theory, and optimization. The paper uses techniques from discrete mathematics, probability theory, and computational geometry, and is likely to be of interest to researchers in several subfields of computer science. Based on the abstract, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.IT (Information Theory), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), cs.CG (Computational Geometry), and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
